WEBVTT

00:00:06.059 --> 00:00:11.220
The theatre in Ephesus was located at the intersection of two of the city's principal

00:00:11.220 --> 00:00:15.779
thoroughfares and was a prominent part of life in that city.

00:00:15.779 --> 00:00:22.379
The theatre, shown in this video, one, could hold 25,000 people, making it the largest

00:00:22.379 --> 00:00:26.059
theatre in Asia Minor in Paul's day.

00:00:26.059 --> 00:00:32.659
Roman theatres were used not only for theatrical performances, but also for hosting debates.

00:00:32.659 --> 00:00:37.299
It was into this theatre that a mob dragged Paul's travelling companions when the

00:00:37.299 --> 00:00:42.700
servicemith Demetrius and his fellow craftsmen stood up a riot against Paul.

00:00:42.700 --> 00:01:01.369
Seen here is two, the Agara, or Marketplace.

00:01:01.369 --> 00:01:08.689
And shown here are three, the Arcadian Way, which led to the Harbour, and four, the location

00:01:08.689 --> 00:01:10.689
of the first century gymnasium.
